{"id":"1107.5823","submitter":"Simon M. Freedman","authors":"Simon M. Freedman and Michael Luke","title":"SCET, QCD and Wilson Lines","comments":"19 pages, 15 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.85.014003","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Soft Collinear Effective Theory (SCET) is an effective field theory which\ndescribes the interactions of low invariant mass jets which are highly boosted\nwith respect to one another. In the standard formulation of SCET, the effective\nLagrangian for collinear fields is expanded in inverse powers of the energy. At\nleading order this leads to manifest decoupling of soft and collinear degrees\nof freedom; however, subleading terms in the effective Lagrangian violate this\nmanifest decoupling. In this paper we point out that the collinear expansion in\nthe SCET Lagrangian is unnecessary, and that the SCET Lagrangian may instead be\nwritten as multiple decoupled copies of QCD. The interactions between the\nsectors in full QCD are reproduced in the effective theory by an external\ncurrent consisting of QCD fields coupled to Wilson lines. We illustrate this\npicture with two examples: dijet production and B->X_s + gamma.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 28 Jul 2011 20:21:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-05-30"}
